  "prompt": "Is it generally understood that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, it is generally well-understood that money laundering is illegal. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. This process makes the funds appear as though they come from a legitimate source.\n\nLaws against money laundering are in place in most countries around the world, often as part of broader efforts to combat organized crime, terrorism, and other illegal activities. Institutions such as banks are typically required to monitor and report suspicious transactions to prevent money laundering. Penalties for money laundering can include heavy fines and imprisonment.\n\nInternational cooperation, such as through the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), also exists to set standards and promote effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.",
